                "href": "/profile/Stanislas-Kowalski"
            },
            "answer_text": "From any of the conquered territories or neighboring countries with which Rome had waged a successful war. That's a lot of options. And since basically all the other nations had similar practices at the time and slave trade was well established, there was practically no limit, as long as transportation was still profitable (no Chinese). Slaves were often referred to by their origins, Gallicus, Spartacus or whatever, but in a very general fashion, for the convenience of their master, as you would call Chinese anyone who comes from Eastern Asia. Supply varied a lot from one period to another, of course. Always remember that Roman history is very very long. Here are some noticable booms in that business: The invasion of Magna Graeca (Southern Italy) provided Rome with a lot of well-educated slaves. This increased considerably Rome's literacy, especially among the dominant class. Buying a Greek teacher was all the rage.The Punic wars established Rome as the dominant power.The Conquest of Greece provided a new supply of good quality slaves: teachers, stewards, prostitutes\u2026The Gallic wars provided a huge amount of hard working slaves. I mean really huge. Some historians estimate that up to one million Gauls were deported during Caesar's campaign. This had some effect on the price.And so on, depending on the ongoing wars. The supply was especially high when the war was hard but victorious. The Romans could deport the entire population of a city that hadn't submitted fast enough and had fought too fiercely.It is of course impossible to know the exact figures, since our sources are limited and the business was quite decentralized. No big record has survived. ",
